# Wireshark Basics

## What is Wireshark

Wireshark is a free, open-source packet analyser. It captures network traffic in real time and lets you inspect every packet — protocol, source, destination, payload, and more. It is essential for network forensics, CTF challenges, and understanding how protocols work.

---

## Installation

```bash
# Kali / Ubuntu
sudo apt install wireshark

# Windows / macOS — download from
# https://www.wireshark.org/download.html
```

---

## Key Concepts

| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| Packet | A single unit of network data |
| Capture | Recording packets from a network interface |
| pcap / pcapng | File format for saved captures |
| Dissector | Plugin that parses a specific protocol |
| Stream | A sequence of related packets (e.g. one TCP connection) |
| Filter | Expression to show/hide specific packets |

---

## Interface Overview

- **Packet List** — top pane, one row per packet
- **Packet Details** — middle pane, protocol layers expanded
- **Packet Bytes** — bottom pane, raw hex and ASCII

---

## Capture Filters vs Display Filters

| Type | When applied | Syntax |
|------|-------------|--------|
| Capture filter | Before capturing — limits what is recorded | BPF syntax |
| Display filter | After capturing — shows/hides packets | Wireshark syntax |

Always use display filters during analysis — they are more powerful.

---

## Essential Display Filters

### Protocol filters
http              — all HTTP traffic

https / ssl / tls — encrypted web traffic

dns               — DNS queries and responses

ftp               — FTP traffic

ssh               — SSH traffic

tcp               — all TCP packets

udp               — all UDP packets

icmp              — ping traffic

smtp              — email sending

### IP and port filters
ip.addr == 192.168.1.1          — traffic to or from this IP

ip.src == 192.168.1.1           — traffic FROM this IP

ip.dst == 192.168.1.1           — traffic TO this IP

tcp.port == 80                  — traffic on port 80

tcp.dstport == 443              — traffic TO port 443

### Combining filters
ip.addr == 10.0.0.1 && http     — HTTP traffic from/to specific IP

http || dns                     — HTTP or DNS traffic

!arp                            — hide ARP packets

tcp.port == 80 && ip.src == 10.0.0.1

### Finding credentials
http.request.method == "POST"       — POST requests (may contain passwords)

ftp.request.command == "PASS"       — FTP passwords in cleartext

http contains "password"            — packets containing the word password

